Wording didn't make sense before. Starting a sentence with "while" implies two contradictory impulses - here, on the one hand, the idea that hijab is not mandatory and, on the other, the insistence by Islamic feminists on observing the practice anyway. Also, it is important to stay focused on Islamic feminists and not Muslim women in general as the previous wording seemed to. The article is on "Islamic feminism", after all.

Formatting changes and improved phrasing to read better and additional background to give a more thorough overview.
Issues with introduction (dispute over women's equality in Iran)

Stating that women are equal in Iran is a political statement. If you think stating that they are not equal is political as well, then the best solution is to not comment on that at all and just state what the law says. I think my edits make for a reasonable compromise by just stating the facts and providing an overall picture which acknowledges those rights that women do have in Iran without being too biased in favor of the IR. Please take any future concerns to the talk page before editing.
Removed kebaya and sarong as these garments are generally not considered Islamic although they historically were worn in some areas which happen to be majority Islamic.

Removed "academic studies on hijab" section. Yes, they are "academic studies", but they center too heavily on Muslim women's opinions. Surprise, surprise - Muslims like hijab. It's like doing an academic study on Christian views of Jesus and citing it as evidence for why everyone should follow his example. Just because something is technically "academic" doesn't mean it should be included if it's not helpful to our understanding of the subject at hand.

message: /* Western perceptions of Iranian women */  Section seems blatantly biased in favor of the Islamic Republic, and does not seem objective. I have thus deleted it on the grounds that it seeks to promote a certain view rather than inform in a neutral manner.

"Ethno-religious" changed to "religious and cultural" because I think this expresses it more clearly. Ethnicity is generally defined as some combination of common descent, language, and culture/religion. Calling it "ethno-religious" may thus confuse people who might conflate criticism or dislike of the hijab and Islam writ large with a dislike of certain ethnicities e.g.Arabs or Persians. While some people who dislike the hijab may also be racist, the objection itself is religious and cultural.
/* Modern history */ Wording edited to clarify that forced veiling in the Islamic Republic of Iran is a contemporary phenomenon and not something that has been relegated to the dustbin of history.
